# Day 2: Stateful Generation

Most tokens in the second agent prompt were already prefetched in the first.
Today you will keep one request cache alive across calls and introduce the
session boundary used throughout the rest of the week.

## The Session Contract

The agent sends messages and receives generated text. An inference session owns
everything below that semantic boundary:

```python
class InferenceSession:
    def __init__(self, model, tokenizer, cache_factory): ...

    def generate(
        self,
        messages: list[Message],
        max_tokens: int,
    ) -> Generation: ...

    def close(self) -> None: ...
```

The object owns:

- the rendered token IDs whose K/V are materialized;
- one cache handle per transformer layer;
- a model, tokenizer, and chat-template identity;
- per-turn reuse and timing counters; and
- an explicit closed state.

It does not own tool execution, workspace files, or the durable conversation.

## Establish a Cache Invariant

For every layer:

```text
cache.offset == len(session.cached_token_ids)
```

Check the invariant before and after every public operation. Generation code has
one subtle edge: a sampled token is not in K/V until it is fed into the next
model call. If decoding stops immediately at a token budget, track that token as
uncached output. The next reconciliation can prefill it normally. Never advance
the logical token count merely because a token was sampled.

All layers must advance together. A mixed set of offsets is corruption, not a
recoverable cache miss.

## Exact-Prefix Reuse

Start with the simplest warm path:

1. render and tokenize the new messages;
2. verify that `cached_token_ids` is an exact prefix of the new prompt;
3. prefill only `new_prompt[len(cached_token_ids):]`;
4. decode the response into the same cache handles; and
5. retain the handles for the next turn.

If the exact-prefix check fails, raise a specific `PromptDiverged` error. Day 3
will replace that limitation with rewind and reconciliation. Do not silently
discard the cache yet because the failing test demonstrates why a stronger
cache API is required.

## Cache Ownership

`InferenceSession.close()` releases each cache exactly once and is idempotent.
The agent CLI should use it as a context manager so exceptions and interrupts do
not leak pages:

```python
with InferenceSession(...) as session:
    result = run_agent(task, session.generate, workspace)
```

The Week 3 model already creates paged request caches backed by model-level page
pools. Keeping a session alive therefore retains its pages and makes memory
ownership visible beyond one request.

## Exercise

1. Implement `InferenceSession` and its cache/token invariants.
2. Reuse a prompt when the new token sequence extends the cached sequence.
3. Reject a divergent prompt without modifying any layer cache.
4. Handle empty suffixes and token-budget termination correctly.
5. Make `close()` idempotent and reject generation after close.
6. Compare warm and cold logits at the append boundary.
7. Report reused and newly prefetched token counts for every turn.

## Checkpoint

An append-only synthetic conversation now reuses K/V across turns. A real chat
template will soon expose why append-only string reasoning is insufficient.

